{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "The significant potential for innovation in these languages resides within their extensive ecosystems of user-contributed libraries or \"packages\"-such as pandas in Python, or ggplot2 in R, that expand a language's capabilities and maintained by a community of voluntary contributors.",
    "Given that GitHub Copilot supported Python and Rust, but not R and Haskell, the staggered support allows us to compare innovation trajectories of these communities without and without LLM assistance.",
    "Building on these foundations, our research addresses multiple research gaps.",
    "While emerging studies examine individual productivity in open-source environments (Song et al. 2024; Hoffmann et al. 2024), they focus on aggregate productivity metrics without examining how LLMs differentially affect the fundamental duality of collaborative innovation processes: capability innovation (that demands deep creative engagement to uncover the challenge itself) and iterative innovation (that focuses on the right answer for a revealed challenge).",
    "This distinction is particularly consequential in collaborative settings where the voluntary nature of contribution means participants self-select into specific innovation types based on their skills, interests, and the contextual information available."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "While emerging studies examine individual productivity in open-source environments (Song et al. 2024; Hoffmann et al. 2024), they focus on aggregate productivity metrics without examining how LLMs differentially affect the fundamental duality of collaborative innovation processes: capability innovation (that demands deep creative engagement to uncover the challenge itself) and iterative innovation (that focuses on the right answer for a revealed challenge)."
  ]
